<DOC><DOCNO> AP891221-0272 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-21-89 2127EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f AM-InsiderTrading     12-21 0353</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Insider Trading,0364</SECOND><HEAD>SEC Accuses 2 Connecticut Men of Insider Trading Scheme</HEAD><BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE><BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Two Connecticut men were accused in a civilcomplaint Thursday of an insider trading scheme involving Saatchi andamp;Saatchi's tender offer for Gartner Group Inc., said federalregulators.   The Securities and Exchange Commission said it filed a civilcomplaint at federal court in Connecticut against Robert CharlesTroup and Helmut August Alpers, both of New Canaan, Conn.   Troup was accused of making $78,812 in illegal trading profitswith insider information about Gartner Group allegedly supplied byAlpers, an executive vice president with the Stamford, Conn.,market research and data processing company.   Alpers, who was not accused of sharing in the alleged ill gottengains, agreed to settle the charges without admitting or denyingwrongdoing, the SEC said.   Alpers consented to an injunction that bars him from violatingfederal securities laws and agreeed to pay $78,812 in penaltiesunder the Insider Trading Sanctions Act, which requires insiderswho share confidential information top pay a sum equal to allegedillegal profits even if they did not share in them.   Troup has not settled the charges, according to the SEC.   Troup's lawyer in Stamford and Alpers' attorney in Washingtonwere not in their offices when called for comment Thursday evening.The SEC complaint did not disclose what Troup did for a living orhow the two men knew each other.   According to the SEC, Alpers allegedly obtained insideinformation in May 1988 that Saatchi andamp; Saatchi, the Britishadvertising agency, intended to acquire Gartner Group and tippedTroup to the upcoming deal a month later.   The SEC complaint alleged that on the morning of June 13, 1988,Troup bought 22,000 shares of Gartner Group common stock, paid forin part with an $82,500 loan from Alpers. Later that day GartnerGroup publicly disclosed that it was engaged in sales discussionswith an unidentified company.   According to the complaint, Troup sold 14,000 Gartner shares onJune 13 and the rest on June 17, after Saatchi andamp; Saatchi publiclyannounced its tender offer for Gartner.</TEXT></DOC>